  "prompt": "What universities can I except to get admitted to with a GRE score of 287 and TOEFL score of 102?",
  "response": "Okay, let's break down your chances with a GRE score of 287 and a TOEFL score of 102.  It's important to be realistic and to consider all factors, not just these two scores.\n\n**Understanding the Scores:**\n\n*   **GRE 287 (Quant + Verbal):** This is a low GRE score.  Many programs, especially in competitive fields, will have average GRE scores well above this. A low GRE score may be overlooked if other aspects of your application are strong.\n*   **TOEFL 102:** This is a good TOEFL score and should meet the requirements of most universities, even those with fairly strict English proficiency standards.  It's generally considered a competitive score.\n\n**Factors Beyond the Scores:**\n\n*   **GPA:** Your undergraduate GPA is crucial. A high GPA can help offset a lower GRE score.\n*   **Statement of Purpose/Essays:** These are your chance to explain your motivations, research interests, and why you're a good fit for the program. A strong statement can significantly improve your chances.\n*   **Letters of Recommendation:** Strong letters from professors who know you well and can speak to your abilities are essential.\n*   **Research Experience:** If you're applying to research-oriented programs (e.g., PhD programs), research experience is vital. Publications, presentations, and lab work are all valuable.\n*   **Work Experience:** Relevant work experience can be a plus, especially for professional programs (e.g., MBA, some Master's).\n*   **Program and Department:**  The competitiveness of the specific program and department you're applying to matters significantly.  Top-ranked departments are much harder to get into, regardless of your scores.\n*   **Specific University Requirements:**  Each university has its own specific requirements and preferences. Some might weigh the GRE more heavily than others. Some programs don't require the GRE at all.\n*   **Your Background:** Underrepresented minorities may sometimes receive special consideration.\n\n**Types of Universities to Target (Realistically):**\n\nGiven your scores, you should primarily focus on universities where:\n\n*   **The GRE is optional or not heavily weighted:** Many universities are moving away from requiring the GRE, or they state that it is only one factor among many. Look for programs that explicitly say they don't emphasize the GRE.\n*   **The program is less competitive:** Consider programs that are newer, smaller, or less well-known.\n*   **Your GPA is high, and you have strong letters and experience:** A high GPA, compelling statement of purpose, and glowing letters of recommendation can compensate for a lower GRE score.\n*   **Your field of study is in high demand and has a shortage of qualified applicants:** Some fields (e.g., certain areas of engineering, computer science, or healthcare) may be more lenient due to high demand.\n\n**Example Universities to Research (This is NOT a guarantee of admission, but places to start looking):**\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Check Specific Program Requirements:** *Always* check the specific admission requirements for the programs you're interested in. Don't rely solely on general university admission requirements.\n*   **Contact the Department:** If you're unsure about your chances, contact the department directly.  Ask if your profile is competitive. Some programs are willing to give you honest feedback.\n*   **Consider Retaking the GRE:**  If you have time and resources, retaking the GRE and focusing on improving your score is the best option. Even a modest improvement can open up more opportunities.\n*   **Apply Broadly:** Don't put all your eggs in one basket. Apply to a range of universities, including some that are a \"reach,\" some that are a \"match,\" and some that are a \"safety.\"\n\n**In summary, while your TOEFL score is good, your GRE score is a significant hurdle.  Focus on programs where the GRE is optional or less important, and make sure the rest of your application is as strong as possible.  Be prepared to apply to a broad range of universities.**\n",
